    "topic": "What is stereotype threat in STEM? Should we address it? And how?",
    "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM is when people feel extra pressure because of negative stereotypes about their group, like women being told they're not good at math or certain minorities not belonging in science fields. This isn't just about hurt feelings—it actually makes people perform worse because they're so worried about confirming the stereotype. I've seen similar things in my work as a carpenter. When someone assumes I can't handle a complex woodworking project because I only have primary school education, I feel that pressure to prove them wrong, and sometimes it makes me second-guess myself even though I know my skills. We absolutely should address stereotype threat because it's holding back talented people who could contribute great things to STEM. When people are worried about stereotypes, they might avoid these fields altogether or not reach their full potential, and that's a loss for everyone. In my creative projects, whether it's knitting intricate patterns or figuring out rock climbing routes, I know that having confidence and not being distracted by doubts makes all the difference. To address it, we need to start by being aware of these stereotypes and calling them out when we see them. In workplaces and schools, creating environments where everyone feels valued and supported is key—like how a good construction crew works together, respecting each person's skills regardless of background. We should also highlight diverse role models in STEM to show that anyone can succeed. From my agnostic perspective, I believe in focusing on what people can do rather than labels. Since I don't use social media, I see this as something that needs real-world action: mentors, fair opportunities, and encouraging curiosity in kids early on. By reducing stereotype threat, we can unlock more innovation and make STEM fields stronger and more inclusive, just like how a well-built structure relies on every piece doing its part.",
